Exploratory Analyses for Missing Data in Meta-Analyses - Vignette

May 2020

Introduction

This vignette is part of the supplementary material to the Exploratory Analyses for Missing Data in Meta-Analyses tutorial. We investigate exploratory analysis methods for diagnosing missing data problems in a meta-analysis, including data visualizations and numerical summaries. Here, we expand results published in our tutorial and detail executable code.

To demonstrate these approaches, we use data on substance abuse interventions for adolescents (Tanner-Smith et al., 2016).These data were extracted from 61 randomized trials and quasi-experiments, and comprise \(k= 95\) different effect size estimates. Each effect involves the difference between two groups of study participants (Group 1 and Group 2). In some cases, reported effects compared a given intervention with some control or business as usual condition, whereas others compared two alternative interventions or implementations. Moreover, the authors were able to identify effect estimates at different time points after intake. Overall, their data includes \(k=328\) effect estimates and \(p=43\) variables describing how and where the intervention was implemented. While none of the effect estimates are missing, there is missingness on some 18 other variables of interest, including the sample composition of studies and the duration and intensity of the intervention.

Using the tools developed in naniar and visdat packages in R (Tierney, 2017; Tierney & Cook, 2018) and some custom extensions, developed specifically for meta-analysis, we aim to work with the four following topics:

  1. Aggregation Plots
  2. Univariate Explorations
  3. Exploring Patterns of Missingness
  4. Numerical summaries for missing data

##Load data and packages

We start by loading the necessary packages and data frame.

library(naniar)
library(ggplot2)
library(visdat)
library(tidyverse)
library(gridExtra)
library(grid)
library(cowplot)
adt_data <- readRDS("../data/adt_data.RDS")

##Clean data

Later, we select relevant variables to the analysis. We include Effect Size estimates, corresponding Standard Errors and 22 covariates related to the intervention.

data <- adt_data %>%
   select(
      `EffectSize` = es_g,
      `StandardError`= se_g,
      `Timing_of_FollowUp`= estimingpost,
      `Design`= design, 
      `Group1_TreatmentCategory`= g1txcat,
      `Group1_TreatmentLocation`=g1loc,
      `Group1_HrsPerWeek`= g1hrsperweek,
      `Group1_TreatmentDays`= g1txdays,
      `Group1_NumSession`= g1numsessions,
      `Group1_MeanAge`=g1age,
      `Group1_PctWhite`= g1perwhite,
      `Group1_PctBlack`=g1perblack,
      `Group1_PctHisp`=g1perhisp,
      `Group1_PctMale`=g1permale,
      `Group2_TreatmentCategory`=g2txcat,
      `Group2_TreatmentLocation`=g2loc,
      `Group2_HrsPerWeek`= g2hrsperweek,
      `Group2_TreatmentDays`= g2txdays,
      `Group2_NumSession`=g2numsessions,
      `Group2_MeanAge`=g2age,
      `Group2_PctWhite`=g2perwhite,
      `Group2_PctBlack`=g2perblack,
      `Group2_PctHisp`=g2perhisp,
      `Group2_PctMale`=g2permale)

Aggregation Plots

Aggregation plots can be a useful starting point when exploring missingness in a meta-analytic dataset. They visualize the entire dataset as a heatmap that indicates which values are missing from which rows. Two examples are presented using the visdat package and the wrapper function gg_summary_covariate_miss.

#summary plots using vis_dat, vis_miss and gg_summary_covariate_miss wrapper function
source("../code/wrappers.R")
gg_summary_covariate_miss(data)

The first plot presents a summary of our dataset structure while highlighting variables with missing data; we can initially identify 18 variables of interest with some missingness. Further, we get a better idea of how much data is missing by looking at the second plot (11.6%).

Univariate Explorations

Univariate plots provide detailed information about how many observations are missing a given variable. Using the gg_miss_var function from the naniar package, we present two approaches to making these plots.

#Summary of missing variables
p1<- gg_miss_var(data) + 
                            labs(y="Missing Cases")+
                            theme(axis.title.x = element_text(size =10),
                                  axis.text.y = element_text(size=6))
                          

#Summary of missing variables (percentage)
p2<- gg_miss_var(data, show_pct=TRUE)+
                                          labs(y="Percentage Missing")+
                                          theme(axis.title.x = element_text(size =10),
                                                axis.text.y = element_text(size=6))
                                                
plot_grid(p1, p2 + 
                    labs(x=""),
                    ncol = 2,
                    labels=c('A','B')
             )

We can identify variables that present a greater number or percentage of missing cases. For example, plot B suggests that the hours per week that the contrast group spent in their assigned condition (Group2_HrsPerWeek) is missing for almost half of the effects in the data.

We can also look at the number of missing values in each case (effect size) by using the gg_miss_case function.

#Missingness in cases. Number of missing values in each case
gg_miss_case(data, order_cases=TRUE) + 
                                            labs(x="Number of Cases")+
                                            labs(y="Missing Variables")

This plot identifies effect size cases with more than 5 or 10 missing covariates. We can see that at least 100 effect size cases are missing at least 5 covariates.

Exploring Patterns of Missingness

We could also be interested in which variables are missing together. Using the gg_miss_upset function, we create an upset plot (Conway, Lex, & Gehlenborg, 2017) to identify the frequency with which different combinations of variables are missing together. We set the number of sets to 11, which is the number of variables that have at least 5 missing points.

gg_miss_upset(data, nsets=11, nintersects=NA)

This plot shows different missingness patterns for our data. Particularly, the first missingness pattern corresponds to rows (effect sizes) where hours per week (Group2_HrsPerWeek_NA), number of days (Group2_TreatmentDays_NA), number of sessions (Group2_NumSession_NA), and location (Group2_TreatmentLocation_NA) of group 2 in this study are all missing. The frequency of occurrence in the data for each pattern is presented in the top part of the plot. For example, this first pattern occurs for 38 effects.

Relating missingness to observed values

We also examine whether missingness in one variable is related to observed values in another variable. This can highlight potential biases in the observed data and also clarify whether data appear to meet the MCAR assumption.

First, we can use the gg_miss_fct function to create a heatmap and understand how different levels of categorical covariates can be related to missingness in other variables. For example, in this plot we explore different types of care provided (columns). For each one of these levels, the cells are shaded according to how frequently those variables are missing.

#Group 2 Treatment Location
gg_miss_fct(x=data, fct=`Group2_TreatmentLocation`)  + 
                                    labs(x="Group 2 Treatment Location")+
                                    theme(axis.text.y = element_text(size=7))

The figure suggests that the percent of subjects who are black or hispanic (Group2_PctBlack and Group2_PctHisp) are much more frequently missing from effects with inpatient treatments than outpatient or continuing care interventions.

A second approach is to plot the level of missingness over the levels of care provided using the gg_miss_case function. For each level of this categorical variable, the plot displays the number of missing cases in each effect size.

#Group 2 Treatment Location
gg_miss_case(x=data, facet=`Group2_TreatmentLocation`) + labs(x="Number of Cases")

The figure shows a larger number of missing cases from effects with outpatient treatments.

Third, effect size estimates and their estimation error variances (or standard errors \(\sigma_i\)) are two relevant variables in most meta-analysis. Density plots are appropriate since we are working with two continuous variables. To facilitate this visualization, we can use the shadow function to keep track of missing values and then create a data frame with the same set of columns, but with the column names added a suffix_NA.

#create shadow dataframe
as_shadow(data)

#Attach a shadow to the current dataframe
adt_shadow <- bind_shadow(data)

Then, we plot three density plots pairs for different variables by using the gg_esse_covariate_miss wrapper function. Each one displays the distribution of effect estimates and standard errors among effects for which a covariate is missing versus when the covariate is observed. Later, to facilitate comparison, we present them in a grid.

source("../code/wrappers.R")
PlotA<- gg_esse_covariate_miss(adt_shadow,
                       es_col = "EffectSize",
                       se_col = "StandardError",
                       covariate = "Group1_HrsPerWeek",
                       adjust = c(1.3, 1.2), # Adjust smoothing for ES and SE densitites
                       label = "Group 1 Hours Per Week", 
                       legend_pos = "top")

PlotB<- gg_esse_covariate_miss(adt_shadow,
                       es_col = "EffectSize",
                       se_col = "StandardError",
                       covariate = "Group1_TreatmentDays",
                       adjust = c(1.3, 1.2), # Adjust smoothing for ES and SE densitites
                       label = "Group 1 Duration of Treatment (Days)", 
                       legend_pos = "top")

plot_grid(PlotA, PlotB, 
          labels=c('A','B'),
          nrow=2)

Plot (A) shows that the covariance duration of treatment (days) for group 1 is mostly missing for larger effect size values. Further, the effect size has larger standard error, when this covariate is missing. Plot (B) illustrates a case where the effect size tends to be closer to zero when a particular covariate is missing. Specifically, when treatment contact (hours per week) for group 1 is missing, both the effect size and its standard errors tend to be smaller than when the covariate is present.

source("../code/wrappers.R")
PlotC<- gg_esse_covariate_miss(adt_shadow,
                       es_col = "EffectSize",
                       se_col = "StandardError",
                       covariate = "Group2_HrsPerWeek",
                       adjust = c(1.3, 1.2), # Adjust smoothing for ES and SE densitites
                       label = "Group 2 Hours Per Week", 
                       legend_pos = "top")
PlotD<- gg_esse_covariate_miss(adt_shadow,
                       es_col = "EffectSize",
                       se_col = "StandardError",
                       covariate = "Group2_TreatmentDays",
                       adjust = c(1.3, 1.2), # Adjust smoothing for ES and SE densitites
                       label = "Group 2 Duration of Treatment (Days)", 
                       legend_pos = "top")

plot_grid(PlotC, PlotD, 
          labels=c('A','B'),
          nrow=2)

Plot (C) shows that both, the effect size and its standard errors, have a similar distribution either when the covariate treatment contact (hours per week) for group 2 is present or not.

Forest plots are very common visualizations in meta-analysis. They can also be a useful to examining the relationship between a covariate and effect sizes of the data set. For instance, the following forest plots are shaded by missingness in treatment contact (hours per week) for each one of the treatment groups.

source("../code/wrappers.R")
#Forest plot shaded by missingness in Group 1 Hrs Per Week
PlotE<- gg_forest_covariate_miss(adt_shadow %>% sample_frac(.5),
                         es_col = "EffectSize",
                         se_col = "StandardError",
                         covariate = "Group1_HrsPerWeek",
                         label = "Group 1 Hrs \nPer Week")

PlotE

#Forest plot shaded by missingness in Group 2 Hrs Per Week
PlotF<- gg_forest_covariate_miss(adt_shadow %>% sample_frac(.5),
                         es_col = "EffectSize",
                         se_col = "StandardError",
                         covariate = "Group2_HrsPerWeek",
                         label = "Group 2 Hrs \nPer Week")

PlotF

Numerical summaries for missing data

Finally, we explore numerical summaries. We can use different functions under naniar to determine raw number, percentages, and proportions of missing observations.

#Total number of missing observations
n_miss(data)
## [1] 917
#Total number of complete observations
n_complete(data)
## [1] 6955
#Proportion missing
prop_miss(data)
## [1] 0.1164888
#Proportion complete
prop_complete(data)
## [1] 0.8835112
#Percentage missing
pct_miss(data)
## [1] 11.64888
#Percentage complete
pct_complete(data)
## [1] 88.35112
#Percentage missing at least one covariate
miss_percentage<- table(rowSums(is.na(data[,3:24])))
1- (miss_percentage[1]/length(data$StandardError))
##         0 
## 0.7378049

We then look at percentage missing by variable and effect size case. Finally, using the miss_ma_var_summary wrapper function, we calculate precision-weighted percentages, which may be more informative in describing the extent of missingness in a meta-analysis.

#Percentage missing by variable
miss_var_summary(data)

References
